<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910104-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>910104-0099.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Rockwell International Corp.:   EPA Signs Consent Accord   And Fines Concern $48,000</HL><DATE>01/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   ROK</CO><IN>DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><GV>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)</GV><LP>   The federal Environmental Protection Agency signed aconsent agreement with Rockwell International Corp. and finedthe company $48,000 for alleged violations in its managementof hazardous wastes at a Palmdale, Calif., facility.   The EPA had cited Rockwell on July 26 for allegedviolations at Air Force Plant 42, Site 3, where the companybuilt the B-1 bomber. Under terms of the consent agreement,Rockwell will revise its waste-analysis plan for the facilityand will provide documentation of a new policy formaintaining stored waste containers and written procedures&quot;to ensure that incompatible wastes will not be storedtogether,&quot; the EPA said. In addition, the company agreed tosubmit documents to the EPA to substantiate future compliancewith federal regulations.</LP><TEXT>   A Rockwell spokesman said that &quot;of the nine violations theEPA cited, five were corrected within one week of their visit{in March 1990}. Another one was corrected in July. Theremaining three are paper workrelated violations, andRockwell is currently revising our internal plans andprocedures so we can be in full compliance with federalregulations.&quot;   Rockwell has interests in the aerospace, electronics,automotive and graphics businesses.</TEXT></DOC>